title: switch back order of session_state_ and execution_providers_ member declarations
body:
**Description**: switches back the order of the session_state_ and execution_providers_ member declarations in InferenceSession

**Motivation and Context**
execution_providers_ is being destroyed before session_state_, and in some winml test cases this causes work to be queued on an executioncontext after it had already been closed which results in an assertion failure. It seems like the order of declaration for these member variables were swapped in this PR (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2449). This causes the order that these members are constructed and destroyed to swap as well, violating the dependency that session_state_ has on execution_providers_.

title: Huge amount of managed allocations in C# API
body:
**Describe the bug**
This is a performance issue. The C# API is unfortunately poorly designed and implemented when it comes to managed allocations for each `InferenceSession.Run`. There is no zero managed allocations path, this is sorely needed for high performance/latency sensitive scenarios.

**Urgency**
We need this within a month. It is likely we will have to do our own C# P/Invoke around the C API to achieve our goals. Long term we would very much like this in here of course :).

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10 64-bit
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Source since we needed TensorRT support
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.1.0
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): MSVC 2019
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.1, 7
- GPU model and memory: 2060 Super

**To Reproduce**
Simply run a an inference loop in say BDN and measure number of managed allocations.

**Expected behavior**
A zero allocation path for `Run` e.g. by reusing instances and outputting into existing instances.

**Screenshots**
Profiling in VS2019 clearly shows the problem. Of about 1.3M allocations 1.1M are from OnnxRuntime, hence we have about 6-7x more allocations due to OnnxRuntime. This causes GC pauses above our budget. All the below allocations are from calling `Run` which is not great.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10798831/71622894-26f96e80-2bd9-11ea-88cf-e92ccd36936e.png)

**Additional context**
Looking at the source for the C# API there seems to be a lot of opportunity to improve this, but the ideal here is to have an API design that allows a zero managed allocation path. Additionally, it would be and is generally advisable that for these kinds of "wrappers" that the underlying C API is exposed in it's raw form, not hidden from advanced users. C API is stable, there is no reason to hide it as such, other than a hand-holding philosophy. :)

Anyone using OnnxRuntime from C# will benefit from this. In a broader context this would relate to how an API can be designed and implemented for high performance scenarios incl. #2754 

Additionally, a proper release for TensorRT is needed too. In many ways a more modular plug-in based model for distribution and packaging seems relevant. 

cc: @tannergooding

title: Reduce BFCArena::FindChunkPtr::kMaxInternalFragmentation.
body:
**Description**: 
Currently we prevent 128MB chunks of memory from the largest bin from being split due to kMaxInternalFragmentation. 
kMaxInternalFragmentation doesn't affect the smaller bins as the test is that the remaining size is > 128MB, and only the largest bin 
(second largest has max of 128MB, so remaining will always be less than 128MB) can possibly satisfy that.

Code involved:

```
void* BFCArena::FindChunkPtr(BinNum bin_num, size_t rounded_bytes, size_t num_bytes) {
  // First identify the first bin that could satisfy rounded_bytes.
  for (; bin_num < kNumBins; bin_num++) {
      ...
      if (chunk->size >= rounded_bytes) {
        ...
        // If we can break the size of the chunk into two reasonably large
        // pieces, do so.  In any case don't waste more than
        // kMaxInternalFragmentation bytes on padding this alloc.
-->     const int64_t kMaxInternalFragmentation = 128 << 20;  // 128mb
        if (chunk->size >= rounded_bytes * 2 ||
-->         static_cast<int64_t>(chunk->size) - rounded_bytes >= kMaxInternalFragmentation) {
          SplitChunk(h, rounded_bytes);
          chunk = ChunkFromHandle(h);  // Update chunk pointer in case it moved
        }
```

body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
With OnnxRuntime 0.5 c# I had a helper model 
[Transposer10.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4036730/Transposer10.zip)
 I would run this utility model just to transpose/permute image data so it could be read correctly by a _target_ model. In OnnxRuntime  0.5 The InferenceSession.Run accepted any input so long as the array length matched the products of the dimensions. This is no longer the case so I have to save the model pre-transposed, or create and load a Transpose model on the fly. In the first case, if using models from elsewhere, this isn't an option. The second solution is difficult from c#.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version 1.1, 
- Windows 10 64bit, 
- Nvidia 1070Ti

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I would like an function to Transpose the NamedOnnxValue, or a function that adds a transpose layer as the top layer of the model as part of the inference session, allowing you to either put in the Axes to be swapped with an `int[]`. In either case the transposition happens on the device.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
The other possibility is that the the previous functionality is returned, but I'm under the impression maybe it isn't possible anymore. I suspect that the extra hardware and the interest of performance have come at the cost of this convenience.

title: MLAS: update SGEMM threading parameters
body:
**Description**: Update the defines used to control SGEMM threading.

**Motivation and Context**
The old code was still structured to handle the Win32 thread pool where there was a high cost to starting a new work item, hence the number of items to be fmadd'ed was coarser. This value is no longer appropriate when using the Eigen threadpool. Updated to use the same value as OpenMP which in ad hoc tests yields good performance (certainly better than before). @snnn ran a performance test and most models were neutral (where GEMMs were already large) and a few models were significantly faster (where some GEMMs now use more threads).

title: speed up Windows TRT CI
body:
currently the CI for Windows TensorRT can take up to 1 hour 50 minutes.
longer term will refactor the CI, but for now there are some improvements that can be made to speed things up significantly.
- don't run onnx tests with CUDA provider when building TRT provider. (saves about 10 minutes)
- remove unneeded build options/tests (dnnl, csharp, gen_doc)
- split debug and release jobs so they can be run in parallel.

with these changes, the debug build takes 30 min and release 47 min. so it can take 47 min when jobs run in parallel.
